[2] Brazil: genomic analysis
Date: October 2017 (ahead of print)
Source: Emerging Infectious Diseases journal [edited]
https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/23/10/17-0307_article


Ref: da Costa AC, Theze J, Komninakis SCV, et al. Spread of chikungunya virus East/Central/South African genotype in Northeast Brazil. Emerg Infect Dis. 2017 [date cited]. https://doi.org/10.3201/eid2310.170307
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Abstract
--------
We investigated an outbreak of exanthematous illness in Maceio by using molecular surveillance; 76 percent of samples tested positive for chikungunya virus. Genetic analysis of 23 newly generated genomes identified the East/Central/South African [ECSA] genotype, suggesting that this lineage has persisted since mid-2014 in Brazil and may spread in the Americas and beyond.

[Approach]
----------
Analyzed samples were from patients who were on average 37 years of age (range 1-86 years); 175 (64 percent) were female, and 198 (73 percent) resided in Maceio municipality. Diagnostic tests for DENV [dengue virus], ZIKV [Zika virus], and CHIKV [chikungunya virus] confirmed that 208 (76 percent) were positive for CHIKV RNA. In addition, 36 (13.2 percent) were co-infected with CHIKV and ZIKV, consistent with Zika virus circulation in Northeast Brazil in mid-2016. We detected no DENV infections. Cycle threshold (Ct) values for CHIKV RNA-positive samples were lower (average Ct = 24.6) than those for ZIKV (average Ct = 33.5).

We applied a metagenomics next-generation sequencing protocol to 38 randomly chosen CHIKV RNA-positive samples. We recovered 23 CHIKV genomes (greater than 4000 bp) by using the MiSeq Sequencer (Illumina, Inc., San Diego, California, USA); mean genome coverage was 72x and mean depth coverage 207x. We also included 2 CHIKV RNA-positive samples from Joao Pessoa, Para√≠ba state. We did not detect the E1-A226V adaptive mutation associated with large outbreaks in Asia in the strains we analyzed. We then appended sequences to publicly available data (659 CHIKV isolates) and used maximum-likelihood and Bayesian phylogenetic analysis to identify the origins of the outbreak.

[Results and conclusion]
------------------------
On the basis of available sequences of isolates from the Americas, the Maceio sequences we analyzed fell within a single strongly supported monophyletic clade (bootstrap support = 99 percent, posterior support = 1.00) that belongs to the ECSA. Genetic analysis suggests the outbreak most likely originated from transmission cycles not previously identified in northeast Brazil and not from a separate introduction into the Americas.

--
